s who trafficked in the shadow economy and the diverse individuals who benefited from their trade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aBlack marketzMexicozMexico Cityy20th century. 0aUrban economics. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  a17th century.  a18th century.  a19th century.  a20th century.  aauthorities.  abaratillo.  ablack market.  acolonial.  acommerce.  acrimes.  acriminal.  aeconomy.  aillegal.  alatin america.  alaw and order.  amarket.  amarketplace.  amercantile.  amexico city.  aneighborhoods.  anorth america.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apost colonial.  ashadow economy.  asouth america.  atepito.  athieves.  atrade.  avendors.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978052029368740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966901/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles